<TEXT>
iran has asked the european airbus 
consortium for help in its search for flight recorders from an 
iranian jetliner that was shot down by an american warship 
the official islamic republic news agency said sunday that 
irans civil aviation organization made the request 
robert alizart a spokesman for the airbus industrie consortium 
in the french city of toulouse said the company received a telex 
wednesday from iran asking where to buy or rent equipment to help 
find the flight recorders 
the a300 was shot down by the us missile cruiser vincennes on 
july 3 and iran said all 290 aboard were killed us military 
authorities said the plane was mistaken for an attacking f14 jet 
fighter 
the pentagon said information gathered by the cruiser showed the 
plane was descending in altitude on an attack profile but iran 
said the plane was climbing 
discovery of the planes two flight recorders in the waters of 
the strait of hormuz could help determine the truth each of the 
black boxes containing the recorders has a radio beacon that can 
transmit for 12 to 30 days after a crash 
alizart says airbus doesnt manufacture the beacons so the 
company is tracking down an agency of the britishbased beacon 
manufacturing company that could provide iran air with the 
equipment it needs to detect the black boxes 
the iranian news agency monitored in cyprus said iranian 
frogmen have searched for the recorders since the plane was shot 
down 
so far 179 bodies have been recovered the agency reported 
