<DOCNO> AP880717-0057 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
some insurance companies say that testing 
more applicants for exposure to aids has benefited the industry by 
helping identify other applicant health problems such as cocaine 
use and diabetes 
life and health insurers are using the opportunity offered by 
increased aids testing to perform more general screenings on the 
blood and urine of applicants when abnormal readings turn up 
insurers sometimes deny applications for coverage or charge higher 
premiums industry officials said 
aids is the best thing that ever happened to the 
lifeinsurance industry said david richman a vice president at 
associated benefits inc in plainville its the best thing as 
far as underwriting insurance companies can now underwrite with 
much more information 
until recent years a consumer could buy several hundred 
thousand dollars of life insurance by answering medical questions 
on an application without submitting to blood or urine tests but 
with growing concern about acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
companies began requiring aids antibody tests of applicants for 
amounts of life insurance above certain threshholds commonly 
100000 worth of insurance 
insurers also often require aids tests of people applying for 
individual health policies travelers for instance requires the 
tests for most of its individual health policies 
companies will not insure people with positive aids antibody 
test results because of the increased likelihood they will develop 
the syndrome and they will not insure cocaine users 
when insurers require blood to be drawn for an aids tests they 
generally have a laboratory screen it for other problems and also 
order a urine test a typical blood and urine screening costs the 
insurer 50 to 75 per person said george kelly an associate 
counsel at hartford insurance group 
the lab checks blood for sugar levels fats and protein and 
looks for signs of cardiovascular disease liver and kidney 
disorders companies also are checking urine for nicotine to 
verify whether people who say they are nonsmokers are telling the 
truth and for problems associated with heavy drinking 
prudential said it is rejecting about 3 percent of applications 
for individual life insurance compared with 2 percent two years 
ago but testa was not sure how much of the increase is due to 
increased blood testing 
aetna would not say how often it denies applications because of 
positive aids tests and said it did not track denials for other 
medical causes 
travelers said testing is revealing more conditions that warrant 
higher rates or rejection of an applicant but spokesman scott 
bushnell said that when an insurer knows it is discovering more of 
its customers problems through tests its rates will reflect fewer 
cost for unknown risks 
if we can better classify peoples mortality risk actuaries 
can sharpen their pencils in terms of pricing kelly said the 
better we can underwrite the more narrowly we can price and 
everyones better off 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

